        <p>When Neil Armstrong stepped down from the Lunar Module and onto the Moon’s ‘Sea of Tranquillity,’ he was
          walking into the most extreme conditions anyone had ever faced – an environment where his chances of survival
          could drop to zero with a single mistake.</p>

        <p>Of course NASA did everything they could to decrease the risk. He was dressed in an 81kg, fireproof suit that
          was 25 layers thick. Custom-fitted with convoluted joints, metal coating and silicon fingertips, it was
          capable
          of surviving micrometeoroid hits, and temperatures ranging from -238F to +248F. And Armstrong himself had been
          selected as one of the world’s most brilliant pilots. In his career he had landed planes missing critical
          parts,
          like wings, and survived tailspins in space after bouncing his rocket off the atmosphere.</p>

        <p>Yet alongside this rarefied technology and training was a rectangle of cloth sewn onto his left glove with a
          series of instructions for his moon walk that read like a shopping list: How many rocks to collect. Where to
          walk. What to photograph. When to set up his experiments.</p>
      </div>
