          Collins christened them “the fourth crew member”. The Lunar Module Armstrong climbed out of had 113 pages of
          checklists all written in key words, abbreviations and acronyms.</p>

        <p>The writing on his glove was simply an extension of this. In 490 characters it contained every instruction
          he’d
          need for his two and a half hours on the Moon.</p>

        <p>The reason was entirely pragmatic. The key to his survival was not just in
          the materials he wore. It was in how he responded psychologically to the unknown. Despite being Commander of
          the mission,
          NASA chose not to rely on something as basic as his memory working. Knowing that he would be in a dangerous
          and
          stressful environment he had never encountered before, they decided it would be better if he didn’t have to
          think. He simply had to look at his clothes and do what they said.</p>
