        <h2>The Physiology Of Survival</h2>

        <p>It’s rarely the cold itself that kills you. It’s the amount of heat your body loses. To stay alive your core
          temperature has to remain within narrowly defined limits. Anything below 95F and you risk
          hypothermia. At 90F
          you’ll start experiencing amnesia. At 82F you’ll lose consciousness. Below 70F you’ll almost certainly
          die.</p>

        <p>As you sink down the scale towards inevitable death, even counting to 10 or doing up a zip may seem
          insurmountable. The colder you get, the less efficiently your brain functions. And even if you can get it to work, using
          it will increase your heat loss. Trying to calculate the probability of your own survival for instance, could
          cut down your life expectancy to ‘some time tomorrow.’</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row wow fadeInUp">
      <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-md-offset-0 col-md-6 left-padded">
        <p>The Condition Black jacket is designed to help you focus on one of the most critical elements of mountain
          survival: keeping your vital organs warm. The warmer you keep them, the higher your body temperature will
          stay.
          While your body will happily sacrifice a couple of fingers or toes, it will only last minutes if your heart,
          lungs or brain stop working.</p>

        <p>Pushing on through exhaustion, or hostile conditions, may feel like it’s going to keep them warm, but it
          ignores one basic equation – if you lose more heat than you make, your body temperature will fall. You can
          still
          become hypothermic in the mountains while moving fast. Even if you have enough energy to carry on you’ll lose
          more than half the heat you produce, as moving your arms and legs blows warm air out and cold air in, and the
          increased blood supply to your muscles raises your surface temperature and increases your heat loss.</p>
      </div>
