        <p>The speed at which you lose heat in the cold depends on the difference between the temperature of your outer
          layer and the temperature of the air around you. The bigger the difference, the more heat you lose. That’s why
          your skin turns cold in the cold. It’s your body limiting blood flow to the surface in order to reduce the
          temperature difference.</p>

        <p>In extreme cold Ceraspace mimics this effect by staying as close to the outside air temperature as possible.
          Designed in a lab to withstand very high temperatures, it has an incredibly low ‘heat up rate,’ which means
          however warm your body is beneath it, the Ceraspace will remain cold and your body will lose less heat.</p>
